div.p:
Kāf is the name of the 22nd letter of the Arabic alphabet. It is pronounced as a voiceless velar stop [k] in Classical and Modern Standard Arabic.
                  In both of these varieties there is no voiced counterpart [g]. In the contemporary spoken dialects, /k/ exhibits less variation than /q/ and /ǧ/;
                  the most widespread innovations are different kinds of affrication.
